7/27/04
  Clipping on frequency adjustment has bad effect on the PLL performance.
  Clipping slows down the convergence.
  Need to do something special when clipping is on!

7/28/04
  Without the dejittering filter, we have a phase error of about 1.5 ms
  at steady state.  With some light amount of dejittering (DJP = 0.025),
  we can reduce the steady state phase error to -0.05 ms.
  However, we don't have a way to determine DJP automatically.

7/29/04
  Noticed that if we initialize the dejitter filter's state (dj_tpi)
  correctly, then the performance is exactly like when we have DJP=1
  with dj_tpi init to 0, independent of what the DJP values are.

  Tried to use adaptive loop filter to see whether we can reduce
  ss phase offset.
  It has a much faster initial response.
  It doesn't help much on the steady state performance!
  
  Tried to use summing loop filter.  But it doesn't work at all.

  Tried to use n-tap averaging filter.  It has the similar performance as
  2-tap IIR.  Interestingly, the ss phase error is almost the same!

  Try to investigate what ss phase error depends on:
    ref: phase error 1.5 ms
    IP delay skew (2 -> 1): 1.75 ms
    IP delay skew (2 -> 3): 1.3 ms
    Noticed that filter error TBO also changes.

    Max IP delay (2000 -> 1000): 0.87 ms
    Max IP delay (2000 -> 4000): 2.9 ms

    Also noticed that the curves are quite different if we change
    the random number generator's seed.
    The initial behavior (e.g. phase error) is quite different,
    but the ss response is about the same!

    Even if we make the source clock the same as reference clock,
    we still have 1.2 ms ss phase error!
    Setting also #TP/IP to 1, get 1.6 ms

  Conclusion: steady state behaviour is independent of the initial
              behavior, but related to the IP network jitter distribution!
